- VSCode Version: 1.7.1
- OS Version: Windows 10

I'm using `WorkspaceConfiguration.update` to try and update existing `launch.json` files due to a change in data passed to our debug adapter. Code looks like this (I don't know if there's a better way; although `update` supports dotted names, this is inside an array?):

```ts
function update_launch_json_change_sdk_to_settings() {
	// Read launch.json config.
	let launchFile = vs.workspace.getConfiguration("launch");

	let configs = launchFile.get<any[]>("configurations");
	if (!configs)
		return;

	let hasChanged = false;

	// Find Dart CLI items that might need upgrading.
	configs.filter(c => c.type == "dart-cli").map(d => {
		// Remove the old sdkPath.
		if (d.sdkPath) {
			console.log("Found old sdkPath, removing...");
			d.sdkPath = undefined;
			hasChanged = true;
		}

		// Add the new debugSettings.
		if (!d.debugSettings) {
			console.log("Didn't find debugSettings, adding...");
			d.debugSettings = "${command.debugSettings}";
			hasChanged = true;
		}
	});

	if (hasChanged)
		launchFile.update("configurations", configs);
}
```

When I look at the changes that were made, the formatting has been lost so it's not obvious what the change was. Since this change is somewhat destructive to the end user, it would be nice if the diff was clean and they could see exactly what was modified.

![Changes](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1078012/20038440/d0ff7d90-a42b-11e6-8493-f8bc4de9548c.png)


Note: The original data was inserted from `initialConfigurations` in our `package.json`, we didn't manually format it.

